I might be counting wrong, but there's six stories in the OP that exceed 20k words. Some probably blast through the 50k mark that qualifies as a short novel.
I can't speak in detail for everyone that has something on the longer side in the OP. What I can say with confidence is that motivation has shit-all to do with it. Different perspectives come out of writing while in different moods.

Start now.
Who is she? Physical description, hundred words or less.
What qualities of hers does the narrator see first? Another hundred words.
There's an event or situation that just happened or is happening now to one or both of them. What was it, and how are they reacting? Another hundred words.

Congrats. You now have three hundred words to build around, chipping away at the blank page on the screen.

People can live in multicultural or multiracial civilizations, but making a society like that is like finding an unicorn, it's hard as fuck and not worth the risk.
A german guy and a french guy can live together just fine, because cultural differences aren't that big of a deal, and most people have no problem with it
People with different morals are way more complicated. For example, if there was a religion which morals included that stomping puppies to death was a good thing, and you were forced to live with a person of this religion, it would take a lot of self-control to keep yourself from stopping the guy, more self-control than the average person, that's where the argument of "only the smartest can get along between races" comes from, it's only the "smartest" people who can realize that moral is relative and (try to) live with other races. And even then, no one wants to hear puppies being smashed all day.
Societies without defined morals (usually defined through religion) are doomed to fail, or a group is going to try to enforce their morals, or they are going to try to separate themselves from the rest.

Of course having people with different cultures also comes with problems, but at least they are not going to rip each others' throat out
